2pt">might </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">be perfectly efficient. Equally, if we overprice some bits of complex surgery</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> we will make people look very good financially </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">when</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> actually they could be very inefficient. That does not help the system overall</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">; i</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">t means that where the problems emerge may not reflect what is underlying</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> them</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">. So I would like much more focus on getting the prices right.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Chair:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">Can we move on?</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q196 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Valerie </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Vaz</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">: </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">As to the </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">extra</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> amount of money, was it £150 million? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text